"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746868","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-04","<p>The government is unable to produce an estimate for the total tax collected from declared income from residential rental properties. This is because income tax receipts cannot be allocated to individual income sources. Individuals may have multiple income sources but pay tax on their total income subject to income tax, after deducting their tax allowances. These allowances and tax rates are not applied to income streams individually but to total taxable income.</p><p> </p><p>The table below provides a breakdown of the number of individual unincorporated landlords by their tax brackets on the basis of the 2014-15 self-assessment returns. Figures in the table reflect outturn data on landlords’ total incomes subject to income tax which includes, among others, rental incomes.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Number of individual landlords by marginal rate, 2014-15 (rounded to nearest thousand)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Basic rate</p></td><td><p>Higher rate</p></td><td><p>Additional rate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1,254,000</p></td><td><p>584,000</p></td><td><p>82,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","2004","2017-07-04T13:55:27.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746868/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746868/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-29","Income Tax: Landlords","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people declaring an income from letting out property pay the (a) additional, (b) higher and (c) standard rates of income tax.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746869","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-04","<p>The government is unable to produce an estimate for the total tax collected from declared income from residential rental properties. This is because income tax receipts cannot be allocated to individual income sources. Individuals may have multiple income sources but pay tax on their total income subject to income tax, after deducting their tax allowances. These allowances and tax rates are not applied to income streams individually but to total taxable income.</p><p> </p><p>The table below provides a breakdown of the number of individual unincorporated landlords by their tax brackets on the basis of the 2014-15 self-assessment returns. Figures in the table reflect outturn data on landlords’ total incomes subject to income tax which includes, among others, rental incomes.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Number of individual landlords by marginal rate, 2014-15 (rounded to nearest thousand)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Basic rate</p></td><td><p>Higher rate</p></td><td><p>Additional rate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1,254,000</p></td><td><p>584,000</p></td><td><p>82,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","2003","2017-07-04T13:55:27.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746869/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746869/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-29","Rented Housing: Tax Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the total tax collected from declared income from residential rental properties was in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746870","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-04","<p>Unincorporated residential landlords are chargeable to income tax on the profits of their rental business.</p><p> </p><p>A landlord who buys a property is liable to stamp duty land tax on the purchase price. A landlord who sells a rental property will pay capital gains tax on any increase in the value of the property.</p><p> </p><p>Unincorporated residential landlords will not usually be registered for VAT as domestic lets are exempt from VAT.</p><p> </p><p>An owner occupier would be chargeable to income tax on any rental income from their property. An owner occupier would also pay stamp duty land tax when they buy a property.</p><p> </p><p>An owner occupier would not pay capital gains tax on the sale of a property that had been their main residence for the whole period of ownership, as this would be exempted by private residence relief.</p><p> </p><p>Owner occupiers would usually be liable for council tax.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-04T13:47:30.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746870/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746870/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-29","Housing: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what taxes related to property are paid by (a) unincorporated residential landlords on properties they rent out and (b) owner occupiers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746871","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-04","<p>As with all aspects of the tax system, the government will keep the taxation of property income under review.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-04T13:51:13.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746871/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746871/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-29","Mortgages: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to review the effect of mortgage interest relief changes as they apply to landlords.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746872","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-04","<p>Using self-assessment data, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) estimated that only 1 in 5 landlords will pay more tax as a result of this measure. No estimate has been made specifically about the number of properties that will be affected by this change. This is because taxpayers currently do not inform HMRC how many properties their finance costs relate to.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-04T13:58:16.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746872/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746872/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-29","Mortgages: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many rental properties will be affected by changes to mortgage interest relief being phased-in since April 2017.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746873","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Government will consider carefully recommendations from the independent pay review bodies before making any decisions on the level of pay award for National Health Service staff.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:32:42.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746873/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746873/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to end the 1 per cent public sector pay cap in the NHS.","true","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","2016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746874","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Government will consider carefully recommendations from the independent pay review bodies before making any decision on the level of pay award for National Health Service staff. The Government accepted recommendations for 2017/18 which have been implemented.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:33:42.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746874/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746874/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to implement the recommendations of independent pay review bodies on NHS pay.","true","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","2017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746875","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-04","<p>If having considered all relevant information and representations, as explained in the answer of 18 April 2017, we reach a final decision in favour of the merger, we will seek Parliamentary approval to the necessary secondary legislation to effect that merger. If Parliament approves the legislation, it will be for the councils concerned to implement the merger. We intend to work with any councils implementing mergers.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-04T16:29:39.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746875/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746875/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Waveney District Council: Suffolk Coastal District Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69471, what plans he has to facilitate the merger of Waveney and Suffolk Coastal district councils to form a new East Suffolk Authority.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","2076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746876","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The total annual rental cost of the new NHS Property Services (NHSPS) offices for London-based staff is £1.37 million excluding VAT, based on a five year lease period; and the total associated costs, including rates, landlord service charges, and facilities management costs, are estimated to be an additional £1.08 million annually.</p><p> </p><p>Gresham Street was the lowest cost of the accommodation options available to NHSPS in London that can accommodate the amount of staff needed. The Company explored the available Government estate, but no premises were large enough or available at the right time.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","2213","2017-07-04T16:30:48.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746876/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746876/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS Property Services: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the total associated annual costs of the new NHS Property Services Limited headquarters in London is.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","2212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746877","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The total annual rental cost of the new NHS Property Services (NHSPS) offices for London-based staff is £1.37 million excluding VAT, based on a five year lease period; and the total associated costs, including rates, landlord service charges, and facilities management costs, are estimated to be an additional £1.08 million annually.</p><p> </p><p>Gresham Street was the lowest cost of the accommodation options available to NHSPS in London that can accommodate the amount of staff needed. The Company explored the available Government estate, but no premises were large enough or available at the right time.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","2212","2017-07-04T16:30:48.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746877/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746877/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS Property Services: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the annual rental cost of the new NHS Property Services Limited headquarters in London is.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","2213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746878","Home Office","false","2017-08-03","<p>In November 2016 the Government published a new five year National Cyber Security Strategy, which is supported by £1.9billion of transformational investment which includes a programme of active cyber defence; the creation of the National Cyber Security Centre, and a dedicated ability to counter-attack in cyber space<strong>.</strong></p><p>The Home Office works closely with both the National Cyber Security Programme and the National Cyber Security Centre to ensure that we have a consistent and joined up understanding of, and approach to the terrorist cyber threat. As set out in the Gracious speech, our counter-terrorism strategy will be reviewed. We will look at our whole counter-terrorism approach across Government, police, local authorities and the security services to ensure they have what they need to protect our country.</p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-08-03T15:22:41.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746878/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746878/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to tackle global cyber terrorism.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr  Dan Poulter","2204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746879","Department for Education","false","2017-07-05","<p>The acquisition cost of the site was £3,000,000, which was assessed to be an appropriate price for the site by the EFA and its advisors.</p><p>Construction costs, professional fees and ICT costs associated with the permanent site for the school are currently commercially sensitive and will be published once the project is completed.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-05T15:33:07.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746879/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746879/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Parkfield School Bournemouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to date has been of the acquisition, adoption and repair of new premises in Hurn, Christchurch for Parkfield Free School.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","2169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746880","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-04","<p>Consideration of the Dorset combined authority proposal is closely interconnected with consideration of the Dorset unitary proposal, submitted on 9 February. Our intention is to announce an initial decision as to how we are minded to proceed on the unitary proposal as soon as practicable, with any such announcement including an indication of how we intend to move forward on the combined authority proposal.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-04T16:23:38.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746880/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746880/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Combined Authorities: Dorset","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to announce his decision on the application made in July 2016 to create a Dorset Combined Authority for economic regeneration and transport infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","2170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746881","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-04","<p>The legislation that provides for licensing of taxi and private hire vehicle (PHV) services is enabling in its nature, giving licensing authorities the discretion to set standards that they deem to be appropriate including language skills. To which end the Department’s current best practice guidance to licensing authorities states that they “may also wish to consider whether an applicant for a taxi or PHV driver licence would have any problems in communicating with customers because of language difficulties.”</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-04T16:28:04.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746881/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746881/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-29","Taxis: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the Government's policy is on whether licensed private hire vehicle drivers are required to pass a test in English as a condition of holding a licence.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","2171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746882","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Government has a manifesto commitment to continue to give local government greater control over the money they raise. We intend to continue to collaborate closely with local government over the coming months on how we will achieve this commitment and it is in this context we will discuss the future of business rates retention pilots.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-04T09:31:09.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746882/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746882/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Non-domestic Rates: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to set out the criteria for applications by lower-tier rural authorities to participate in a pilot for 100 per cent business rates retention.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","2172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746883","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-04","<p>On 21 June 2017 Natural England published its proposals for coastal access for the 41 mile stretch of the coast between Kimmeridge Bay and Highcliffe, Dorset. There is a now an eight week consultation period for representations to be made on the proposals. The closing date for representations is midnight on 16 August 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We will then consider Natural England’s proposals in the light of such representations.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-07-04T16:32:43.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746883/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746883/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-29","Public Footpaths: Christchurch","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make it his Department's policy to require Natural England to designate the proposed route of the national coastal footpath in Christchurch constituency as being from Highcliffe to Mudeford Quay and across the Avon estuary direct to Hengistbury Head; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","2173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746884","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>Local authorities have strong powers to deal with poor quality, unsafe accommodation and we expect them to use those powers. Under the Housing Health and Safety Rating System (HHSRS), local authorities can issue an Improvement Notice or a Hazard Awareness Notice if they find a defect in the property. Failure to comply with an Improvement Notice is a criminal offence for which local authorities can impose a financial penalty of up to £30,000 or prosecute in the courts which have the power to impose an unlimited fine. In extreme circumstances, the local authority may decide to make repairs themselves, or to prohibit that property from being rented out. The HHSRS applies to all residential properties, regardless of who owns them. Leases will normally also provide a landlord with the right to inspect in good faith where there is concern about the maintenance or repair.</p><p>The Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 places a duty on housing providers to undertake a fire risk assessment of the common parts of their properties and to put in place and maintain adequate fire precautions to manage the risk that lives could be lost in a fire. The Order is enforced by fire and rescue authorities. Failure to comply with the provisions of the Fire Safety Order may to lead to prosecution and potentially a significant fine or custodial sentence.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-14T11:04:39.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746884/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746884/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to enable councils to access flats bought under right to buy in order to undertake compliance checks for fire safety.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","1992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746885","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005, known as the Fire Safety Order, applies to all business and commercial premises, and to other premises to which the public have access. It requires the ‘responsible person’ (usually the employer, owner, the landlord, freeholder or managing agent) to carry out and review regularly a fire risk assessment and put in place - and maintain in good working order - fire precautions which are adequate and appropriate to manage the risk that lives could be lost in the event of a fire.</p><p>The level of competency required for individual premises will vary according to their nature and complexity. The responsible person may decide that they are competent to carry out the risk assessment themselves or they may choose to appoint a competent person to undertake the risk assessment on their behalf. The requirements for a competent person are set out in the Order. A person is to be regarded as competent for the purposes of making a fire risk assessment if they have sufficient training and experience or knowledge and other qualities to enable them properly to assist in undertaking the preventive and protective measures.</p><p>To help those responsible for ensuring that the risk from fire in their premises has been accurately assessed, the fire sector has produced guidance on how to choose a competent fire risk assessor. This is available on <a href="http://www.cfoa.org.uk/19532" target="_blank">www.cfoa.org.uk/19532</a></p><p>In addition, fire safety risk assessment guidance produced by the Government and by the Local Government Association, also provides advice and guidance to those responsible for fire safety compliance to help them to accurately assess the risks from fire and implement adequate and appropriate fire safety measures. This is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/workplace-fire-safety-your-responsibilities/fire-risk-assessments" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/workplace-fire-safety-your-responsibilities/fire-risk-assessments</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-07T15:29:23.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746885/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746885/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Public Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the legal requirements are for (a) fire risk assessments to be undertaken by a competent person and (b) who is able to carry out fire risk assessments on large public buildings.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","2152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746886","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Criminal Cases Review Commission’s review of the applications from the ‘Shrewsbury 24’ is progressing. The Commission are currently considering additional documentation relating to this case. I know that the CCRC will consider this - and the views of the applicants about this material - with care. I understand that the Commission hope to complete their review of this case before the end of the year.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-07T13:42:20.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746886/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746886/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746886/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-29","Industrial Disputes: Shrewsbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress the Criminal Cases Review Commission has made on its review into the Shrewsbury 24 case.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746887","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>Each year the National Crime Agency publishes statistics on the European Arrest Warrants (EAW), these figures include: -</p><p> </p><ul><li>The number of EAWs made or received</li><li>The number of arrests</li><li>The number of surrenders</li></ul><p> </p><p>The figures since 2010 are published at: -</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics" target="_blank">http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2107 ; 2200","2017-07-07T08:45:07.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746887/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746887/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many European Arrest Warrant (a) arrests, (b) requests and (c) surrenders have been made in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746888","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>In a modern, interconnected world, crime is increasingly international and does not respect borders. The Government is clear that effective cooperation with EU Member States on security, justice and policing in order to tackle serious organised crime will continue to be a top UK priority.</p><p> </p><p>The Government values the role of Europol and that is why the UK opted-in to the new Europol Regulation, which came into force on 1 May 2017, enabling us to maintain our current access to the agency and benefit from its cooperation and operational advantages until we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Intelligence exchange between UK law enforcement and Europol is well-established and takes place on a daily and routine basis on a wide range of criminal activity. The National Crime Agency (NCA) also support Europol with seconded staff. This cooperation continues to assist UK efforts to tackle cross-border crime impacting on the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The specific data requested on how Europol operations and investigations have contributed to seizures, arrests and prosecutions in the UK is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2100 ; 2109","2017-07-07T08:54:42.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746888/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746888/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many kilograms of (a) drugs, (b) new psychoactive substances and (c) endangered species goods have been seized in the UK as a result of Europol operations in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746889","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>In a modern, interconnected world, crime is increasingly international and does not respect borders. The Government is clear that effective cooperation with EU Member States on security, justice and policing in order to tackle serious organised crime will continue to be a top UK priority.</p><p> </p><p>The Government values the role of Europol and that is why the UK opted-in to the new Europol Regulation, which came into force on 1 May 2017, enabling us to maintain our current access to the agency and benefit from its cooperation and operational advantages until we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Intelligence exchange between UK law enforcement and Europol is well-established and takes place on a daily and routine basis on a wide range of criminal activity. The National Crime Agency (NCA) also support Europol with seconded staff. This cooperation continues to assist UK efforts to tackle cross-border crime impacting on the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The specific data requested on how Europol operations and investigations have contributed to seizures, arrests and prosecutions in the UK is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2099 ; 2109","2017-07-07T08:54:42.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746889/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746889/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many weapons have been seized in the UK as a result of Europol operations in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746890","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Prime Minister has made clear that one of the twelve objectives for the negotiations ahead will be to establish a new relationship with the European Union that includes practical arrangements on matters of law enforcement cooperation to tackle cross-border crime and to keep our people safe.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with EU partners and we are examining the options for future cooperation on measures such as SIS II once the UK has left the EU but it is too early to speculate at this stage what future arrangements may look like.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-07T08:49:23.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746890/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746890/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Crime: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential loss of access to the Schengen Information System on tackling crime after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746891","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>Each year the National Crime Agency publishes statistics on the European Arrest Warrants (EAW), these figures include: -</p><p> </p><ul><li>The number of EAWs made or received</li><li>The number of arrests</li><li>The number of surrenders</li></ul><p> </p><p>The figures since 2010 are published at: -</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics" target="_blank">http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2083 ; 2200","2017-07-07T08:45:07.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746891/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746891/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many European Arrest Warrants have been requested by each police force since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746892","Home Office","false","2017-08-03","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. INTERPOL releases information annually detailing the total results of Operational Pangea from all participating countries.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-08-03T14:18:49.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746892/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746892/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Drugs: Counterfeit Manufacturing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) websites have been shut down, (b) goods have been seized, (c) arrests have been made and (d) medicine units have been seized in the UK under Operational Pangea in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746893","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>In a modern, interconnected world, crime is increasingly international and does not respect borders. The Government is clear that effective cooperation with EU Member States on security, justice and policing in order to tackle serious organised crime will continue to be a top UK priority.</p><p> </p><p>The Government values the role of Europol and that is why the UK opted-in to the new Europol Regulation, which came into force on 1 May 2017, enabling us to maintain our current access to the agency and benefit from its cooperation and operational advantages until we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Intelligence exchange between UK law enforcement and Europol is well-established and takes place on a daily and routine basis on a wide range of criminal activity. The National Crime Agency (NCA) also support Europol with seconded staff. This cooperation continues to assist UK efforts to tackle cross-border crime impacting on the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The specific data requested on how Europol operations and investigations have contributed to seizures, arrests and prosecutions in the UK is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2099 ; 2100","2017-07-07T08:54:43.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746893/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746893/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) arrests and (b) prosecutions have taken place in the UK after Europol investigations into missing trader intra-community fraud in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746894","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>Each year the National Crime Agency publishes statistics on the European Arrest Warrants (EAW), these figures include: -</p><p> </p><ul><li>The number of EAWs made or received</li><li>The number of arrests</li><li>The number of surrenders</li></ul><p> </p><p>The figures since 2010 are published at: -</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics" target="_blank">http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","2083 ; 2107","2017-07-07T08:45:07.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746894/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746894/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many European Arrest Warrants have (a) been issued by the UK, (b) resulted in an extradition back to the UK and (c) resulted in an extradition back to the country requesting the warrant in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746895","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Government will look to establish a new relationship with the European Union that includes practical arrangements on matters of law enforcement cooperation to tackle cross-border crime and to keep our people safe.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with the Crown Prosecution Service on the options for future cooperation once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-07T08:38:54.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746895/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746895/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746895/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect on the Crown Prosecution Service of the potential loss of access to the European Arrest Warrant.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","2201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746896","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-07","<p>The consultation on the draft Airports National Policy Statement closed on 25 May, and we are analysing the tens of thousands of responses received. The Government will set out the next steps in the process in due course.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-07T07:39:36.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746896/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746896/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-29","Airports: National Policy Statements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, in which month the final National Airports Policy Statement will be published.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","2080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746897","Department for Education","false","2017-07-05","<p>We will set out the outcome of the schools national funding formula consultation in due course, including details of the protections for school budgets and allocations for each school. We remain committed to introducing a formula that is fair, while also ensuring sufficient stability across the system.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-05T16:03:32.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746897/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746897/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to her oral contribution of 27 June 2017, Official Report, column 487, whether her commitment that no school will have its budget cut as a result of the new national funding formula means that school budgets will be protected in (a) real terms or (b) cash terms.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","2039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746898","Department for Education","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Government has made clear its commitment to continue to support all good and outstanding schools to expand where there is a need for more good school places. Any proposals to expand onto a satellite site would need to demonstrate that they are an expansion of an existing school, and a decision would be made on the circumstances of each case.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-05T16:05:49.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746898/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746898/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Grammar Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2017 to Question 128, if her Department supports (a) the expansion of existing grammar schools and (b) the opening of satellite sites of existing grammar schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","2072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746899","Department for Education","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Secretary of State is considering the School Teachers’ Review Body’s report and its recommendations. We will publish the report, together with our response and a draft revised School Teachers’ Pay and Conditions Document in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-05T16:17:33.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746899/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746899/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746899/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Schools: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans her Department has to end the public sector pay cap for school staff.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","2073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746900","Department for Education","false","2017-07-05","<p>This Government will continue to work to ensure that every child has the opportunity to attend a good school and that all schools are fairly funded. The core schools budget has been protected in real terms since 2010 and is set to rise from £41bn in 2017-18 to over £42bn in 2019-20 with increasing pupil numbers. We are considering the more than 25,000 responses we received to the National Funding Formula consultation, and will publish our response in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-05T16:16:14.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746900/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746900/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746900/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Secretary of State for Education's oral contribution of 27 June 2017, Official Report, column 487, how much additional funding she has allocated to ensure that no school loses funding as a result of the implementation of the national funding formula for schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","2163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746901","Department for Education","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Budget 2017 allocated additional capital funding to enable free school applications to be approved in 2017-18 and beyond. We will confirm arrangements in due course.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-05T16:19:54.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746901/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746901/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746901/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to line 2 of table 2.1 of the Spring Budget 2017 and pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2017 to Question 128, how much of the funding for new free schools and new selective schools allocated in the 2017-18 financial year has been spent to date.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","2217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746902","Department for Education","false","2017-07-07","<p>My Rt hon. Friend, the Minister of State for School Standards, confirmed on 4 July that infants will continue to receive universal infant school meals.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-07T13:55:25.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746902/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746902/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746902/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Primary Education: Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to review funding for universal infant free school meals.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746903","Department for Education","false","2017-07-07","<p><em>Childhood obesity: a plan for action</em>, published in August 2016, included a commitment to introduce a new voluntary healthy rating scheme for primary schools to recognise and encourage their contribution to preventing obesity</p><p> </p><p>We are now reflecting on the feedback received from interested parties and we will come forward with proposals to take the scheme forward in due course. . The Department for Education published a prior information notice on 20 December 2016, which gave potential suppliers an overview of the type of services required by this scheme. In spring 2017, the department held meetings with interested suppliers to discuss the scheme.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-07T13:31:12.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746903/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746903/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746903/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Healthy Schools Rating Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress she has made on the introduction of the healthy schools rating scheme.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746904","Department for Education","false","2017-07-07","<p>The new example menus for early years settings are to be published in due course. We will set out our plans for publicising the menus at that time.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-07T13:31:51.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746904/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746904/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746904/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Pre-school Education: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to publish the new early years menus for childcare settings; and what plans she has to publicise those menus.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746905","Department for Education","false","2017-07-07","<p>The School Food Standards, where they apply, provide the legislative framework to ensure schools provide pupils with healthy food and drink options. In <em>Childhood obesity: a plan for action</em>, published in August 2016, we indicated that we will update the standards in light of refreshed government dietary recommendations, and we have committed to reviewing the standards to align with the latest scientific advice on sugar.</p><p>We are in the process of confirming the timelines for this piece of work and further information will be available in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-07T13:40:02.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746905/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746905/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746905/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Schools: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to review and update school food standards.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746906","Department for Education","false","2017-07-11","<p>We are concerned that some summer born children, whose parents opt to defer entry may be missing the reception year where the essential teaching of early reading and arithmetic takes place. We are giving careful consideration to how we might make any changes. Further information will be available in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-11T16:49:13.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746906/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746906/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746906/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to update her Department's guidance on summer-born children: school admission.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746907","Home Office","false","2017-07-04","<p><strong></strong>The Home Office collects data on the number of anti-social behaviour incidents recorded by the police forces in England Wales. It is not possible to tell from these data how many incidents related to vehicles or the type of vehicle involved.</p><p>Anti-social behaviour incidents recorded by the police are published by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesbulletintables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesbulletintables</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-04T13:48:18.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746907/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746907/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Antisocial Behaviour: Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many reports of anti-social behaviour connected with (a) off-road bicycles, (b) quad bikes and (c) mopeds there were in each police authority area in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","2136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746908","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Government does not hold a central inventory of software used by departments. However, the National Cyber Security Centre has encouraged any victims or potential victims of the recent malware incident to contact them directly.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-05T16:23:19.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746908/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746908/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-29","Government Departments: Computer Software","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether any Government Departments use Medoc software.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","2147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746909","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-10","<p>The UK position is that Total Allowable Catches (TAC) for all species should be should be set in line with the science to ensure we have sustainable fisheries. On leaving the EU, the UK will become an independent coastal state with responsibility for managing its EEZ and this will be an opportunity to reach new agreements on access arrangements and the UK share of the TAC for some species.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-07-10T16:35:31.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746909/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746909/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-29","Fisheries: Quotas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has made an assessment of the effect on fishing quota levels for (a) cod, (b) haddock, (c) coley, (d) monkfish, (e) prawn, (f) halibut, (g) mackerel, (h) herring and (i) whiting of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","2067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746910","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Traffic Commissioner for Wales has use of an office in Cardiff as a temporary measure whilst the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) takes forward plans to locate a permanent base in Cardiff.</p><p> </p><p>Work is being undertaken by DVSA Estates to agree a lease and layout plan for premises in St Mary’s Street, Cardiff. It is expected that the traffic commissioner will move into this office in September 2017.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-07T07:24:26.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746910/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746910/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-29","Traffic Commissioners: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to relocate the Traffic Commissioner for Wales to an office in Wales.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","2192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746911","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-04","<p>Since April 2012, UK Export Finance (UKEF) has provided support to 25 businesses exporting to Argentina, Brazil and Peru. UKEF does not hold centrally figures for companies that have applied or enquired about its support. The numbers of companies that UKEF has supported by nation are provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Argentina</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Brazil</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Peru</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales*</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*One company’s headquarters are based in England but has major manufacturing centres in both England and Wales.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-04T16:07:30.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746911/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746911/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746911/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-06-29","Export Credit Guarantees: South America","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many companies from (a) England, (b) Wales, (c) Scotland and (d) Northern Ireland have applied for export credit support for trade with (i) Argentina, (ii) Brazil and (iii) Peru in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","2168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746912","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-04","<p>We are investing £1.3 billion to reform and modernise the prison estate to replace ageing and ineffective prisons with up to 10,000 modern prison places. On 22 March 2017, the then Lord Chancellor and Secretary of State for Justice announced plans for the building of four new prisons in England and Wales, replacing old and overcrowded establishments with new, fit for purpose buildings. This is in addition to our plans to redevelop the sites at the former HMP Wellingborough and at HMP &amp; YOI Glen Parva.</p><p> </p><p>The plans include a new prison in Port Talbot in South Wales. The Ministry of Justice intends to apply for planning permission in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-04T14:13:07.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746912/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746912/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746912/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-29","Prisons: Port Talbot","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his Department's policy is on building a new prison in Port Talbot.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","2008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746913","Home Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Home Office collects data on the number of stalking offences recorded by the police forces in England and Wales. Information on these offences can be found in the Home Office Open Data Tables for police recorded crime, available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We expect the police to investigate all crimes that are reported to them. All forces will suspend crime investigations if, after initial investigation, they conclude that there are no further lines of enquiry to pursue because there is no evidence trail or witnesses. These decisions are an operational matter for forces, but investigations can be reopened at any time should further evidence come to light. Information on the outcomes of offences recorded by the police is routinely published by the Home Office and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/crime-outcomes-in-england-and-wales-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/crime-outcomes-in-england-and-wales-statistics</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-08T09:12:43.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746913/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746913/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746913/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Stalking: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many reports of stalking were made to each police force in Wales in (a) 2015 and (b) 2016; and how many of each were investigated by the police.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","2137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746914","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-06","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my answer given to PQ 1092 and 1105 on 4<sup>th</sup> July 2017. As I said then, on 18 January the previous government announced that it would set out a strategy for victims of crime within 12 months, and that it would take the appropriate action to give effect to the strategy.</p><p> </p><p>We have also committed to enshrine victims’ entitlements in law, making clear what level of service they should expect from the police, courts and criminal justice system. Now the election has passed further consideration can be given to this work. We will announce further details in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-06T15:07:21.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746914/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746914/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746914/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-29","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department plans to bring forward legislative proposals to put the Victims Code into law.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","2241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746915","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-06","<p>In March 2017 the Commonwealth Trade Ministers' Meeting was held in London. My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade and my noble Friend the Minister of State for Trade Policy met over 20 trade ministers from across the Commonwealth. My Ministerial colleagues and I continue to have a range of contacts with counterparts from the Commonwealth, both specifically in preparation for the 2018 Commonwealth Summit and as part of our ongoing bilateral trade relationships.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-06T11:16:01.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746915/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746915/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746915/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-06-29","Overseas Trade: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions has he had with his counterparts in Commonwealth countries on the future of trade and investment between the UK and other member states.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","2081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746916","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) Impact trial will seek to engage as many of the approximately 230 genitourinary medicine clinics in England as possible. All clinics will be offered the opportunity to participate, regardless of where they are situated. In keeping with the open access nature of sexual health services, patients will be able to attend any clinic in England that is participating in the trial and therefore have their trial eligibility assessed regardless of where they live.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England and Public Health England have stated that the trial will begin by the summer of 2017, available to view here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/update-on-prep-impact-trial-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/update-on-prep-impact-trial-in-england</a></p><p> </p><p>The final timescale will be considered at the July meeting of the PrEP Programme Oversight Board (POB) when updated information on the likely timeline of availability of trial drug at trial sites will be provided. Several bids to supply the trial drug were received on the June 29 deadline. If the trial timeline needs to change, new information will be provided in the Stakeholder Update due to be issued after the July 14 PrEP POB.</p><p> </p><p>The Frequently Asked Questions will be published following review at the July meeting of the PrEP POB.</p><p> </p><p>The PrEP Impact trial application was submitted to the Research Ethics Committee (REC) at the end of June. The committee will issue a final ethical opinion within 60 days. The current expectation is that approval will be obtained in time for the drug becoming available. The REC approval timeline is independent of the trial drug procurement process.</p><p> </p><p>Before a trial site can begin to recruit patients, they must provide confirmation of capacity and capability to the Trial co-ordination centre and the timescales for this can vary across localities. This process includes negotiating and finalising local trial contracts and having site staff undergo trial-specific training provided by the Trial co-ordination centre (St Stephen’s Clinical Research). This process will occur in parallel to obtaining national ethics approval and the trial drug procurement activities. Some sites may be in a position to begin trial participant recruitment as soon as the trial drug becomes available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","2010 ; 2011 ; 2012 ; 2013","2017-07-04T11:10:26.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746916/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746916/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746916/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","HIV Infection: Clinical Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to Public Health England's announcement of 20 June 2017 on the HIV PrEP Impact trial in England, what steps are being taken to ensure that high-risk patients are able to access the trial outside London, Manchester and Brighton.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","2009"
