"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746920","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) Impact trial will seek to engage as many of the approximately 230 genitourinary medicine clinics in England as possible. All clinics will be offered the opportunity to participate, regardless of where they are situated. In keeping with the open access nature of sexual health services, patients will be able to attend any clinic in England that is participating in the trial and therefore have their trial eligibility assessed regardless of where they live.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England and Public Health England have stated that the trial will begin by the summer of 2017, available to view here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/update-on-prep-impact-trial-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/update-on-prep-impact-trial-in-england</a></p><p> </p><p>The final timescale will be considered at the July meeting of the PrEP Programme Oversight Board (POB) when updated information on the likely timeline of availability of trial drug at trial sites will be provided. Several bids to supply the trial drug were received on the June 29 deadline. If the trial timeline needs to change, new information will be provided in the Stakeholder Update due to be issued after the July 14 PrEP POB.</p><p> </p><p>The Frequently Asked Questions will be published following review at the July meeting of the PrEP POB.</p><p> </p><p>The PrEP Impact trial application was submitted to the Research Ethics Committee (REC) at the end of June. The committee will issue a final ethical opinion within 60 days. The current expectation is that approval will be obtained in time for the drug becoming available. The REC approval timeline is independent of the trial drug procurement process.</p><p> </p><p>Before a trial site can begin to recruit patients, they must provide confirmation of capacity and capability to the Trial co-ordination centre and the timescales for this can vary across localities. This process includes negotiating and finalising local trial contracts and having site staff undergo trial-specific training provided by the Trial co-ordination centre (St Stephen’s Clinical Research). This process will occur in parallel to obtaining national ethics approval and the trial drug procurement activities. Some sites may be in a position to begin trial participant recruitment as soon as the trial drug becomes available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","2009 ; 2010 ; 2011 ; 2012","2017-07-04T11:10:26.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746920/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746920/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","HIV Infection: Clinical Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to Public Health England's announcement of 20 June 2017 on the HIV PrEP Impact trial in England, how long he expects genitourinary medicine clinics and trial sites to take to prepare in readiness for the trial once the drug procurement contract for the trial has been agreed.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","2013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746921","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The commissioner – in this case Dudley Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) – is solely responsible for carrying out the procurement and it will be for the commissioner to determine break points, penalties, compensation and arrangements to ensure continuity of service.</p><p> </p><p>As with all standard National Health Service contracts, we would expect any multi-speciality community provider (MCP) contract to set out the circumstances in which the contract may be terminated by either party and the process following termination. It will be for the CCG to determine where the break points should be, factoring in the potential impacts on value for money. In accordance with the existing terms of the NHS Standard Contract, there will be a 12 month no fault termination clause.</p><p> </p><p>The Dudley MCP contract will ensure that in the event of a provider not meeting their obligations, and where there is a need for an early termination, the provider will be required to pay the commissioners any additional costs and expenses incurred as a result of the termination. This will include those incurred in recommissioning the services covered by the contract from an alternative provider for the rest of the term of the contract as well as ensuring service continuity.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","2022 ; 2024","2017-07-04T14:41:22.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746921/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746921/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Health Services: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what (a) penalties or (b) compensation would apply in the event of early termination of the contract for Dudley's multi-speciality community provider.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","2023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746922","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-04","<p>Arms sales data by region are published annually on GOV.UK.</p><p>The Government publishes Official Statistics about export licences granted and refused each quarter. The data currently includes details of licences up to 31 December 2016. Data for the period 1 January 2017 to 31 March 2017 will be published on 18 July 2017. The data can be accessed on GOV.UK</p><p>Licences granted are not necessarily a measure of exports shipped in a given period as they are valid for between two and five years. Licensing data only provides a partial indication of sales as exporters only declare export values for a subsection of licences (Standard Individual Export Licences). Some licences expire before they are used and in these circumstances exporters must submit a further application, which can result in an element of double counting.</p><p>The value of arms export licences issued from 2010 to 2017 are:-</p><p>Year Value (£)</p><p>2010 £3,082,468</p><p>2011 £439,488</p><p>2012 £354,419</p><p>2013 £4,255,887</p><p>2014 £10,547,414</p><p>2015 £140,925,288</p><p>2016 £1,822,648</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-04T16:21:02.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746922/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746922/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-06-29","Arms Trade: Qatar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what arms sales between the UK and Qatar were carried out from 2010 to 2017.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","2015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746923","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The commissioner – in this case Dudley Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) – is solely responsible for carrying out the procurement and it will be for the commissioner to determine break points, penalties, compensation and arrangements to ensure continuity of service.</p><p> </p><p>As with all standard National Health Service contracts, we would expect any multi-speciality community provider (MCP) contract to set out the circumstances in which the contract may be terminated by either party and the process following termination. It will be for the CCG to determine where the break points should be, factoring in the potential impacts on value for money. In accordance with the existing terms of the NHS Standard Contract, there will be a 12 month no fault termination clause.</p><p> </p><p>The Dudley MCP contract will ensure that in the event of a provider not meeting their obligations, and where there is a need for an early termination, the provider will be required to pay the commissioners any additional costs and expenses incurred as a result of the termination. This will include those incurred in recommissioning the services covered by the contract from an alternative provider for the rest of the term of the contract as well as ensuring service continuity.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","2022 ; 2023","2017-07-04T14:41:22.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746923/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746923/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Health Services: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans are in place to ensure continuity of care in the event that an operator of the contract for Dudley's multi-speciality community provider terminated that contract early.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","2024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746924","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-04","<p>The UK is supporting Guinea to strengthen its routine health and immunisation systems, through the UK’s investment in Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance. In 2016 Gavi immunised over 2 million children with measles vaccine in Guinea, and will support Guinea to introduce measles into its routine vaccination programmes in the future.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-04T14:27:09.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746924/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746924/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-06-29","Guinea: Measles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance her Department is giving to improve routine measles vaccination programmes in Guinea.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746925","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-04","<p>We have initiated testing in priority buildings across the public sector, including hospitals, schools, colleges and universities. We are prioritising testing on buildings where people sleep overnight, which have Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding and are of a certain height. Where appropriate, organisations are working with the fire and rescue service to put in place precautionary safety checks and measures. We have set up an expert panel to advise us on any immediate steps that should be taken to ensure fire safety, and we will act on those. The role of the expert panel and the advice already given following Grenfell is set out in a note published last week at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-04T16:44:22.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746925/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746925/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Buildings: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has conducted checks of the type carried out on residential buildings at (a) NHS hospitals, (b) schools, (c) colleges, (d) universities and (e) other public buildings.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","2018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746926","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has sent no such letter.</p><p> </p><p>On 24 June, Jim Mackey, the chief executive of NHS Improvement, sent an e-mail to all National Health Service trust and foundation trust chief executives, seeking their urgent and full co-operation in inspecting their properties, and outlining the help that would be available to them. It said:</p><p> </p><p>“Dear colleagues,</p><p>I would be grateful for your immediate help with the urgent actions outlined in this email. Please cascade this to the relevant on-call directors and estates on-call within your organisations.</p><p>Thank you for the enormous effort that you and your teams have put in to completing the questionnaires sent last week, following the tragic events at Grenfell Tower.</p><p>Following discussions with Secretary of State, I am requesting that we take further proactive and precautionary measures and instigate, with immediate effect, an inspection by your local fire and rescue services of all your properties by close of play tomorrow evening, to ensure that there are no urgent risk safety risks. I am aware that many of you have already undertaken a fire assessment with the relevant fire authorities – so please only take action if you have not done so already.</p><p>Upon completion of this inspection, please confirm by way of letter (signed by both trust CEO and fire inspector) that this has been concluded, and whether there are any immediate risks that need resolving. We will then work with trusts directly where an urgent decisions are required. Please send your email confirmation and attachment to [redacted]</p><p>We understand that it might be difficult to mobilise support from your end at such short notice, and so efforts are in train to ensure that these actions are also prioritised through Home Office.</p><p>You will also be aware, from [redacted] letter on Monday, that we will be taking action to mobilise further local support where this is required. This process is being managed in parallel to this request.</p><p>Once again may I thank you for you cooperation in this matter.</p><p>Best wishes</p><p>Jim”</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:35:01.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746926/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746926/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish (a) his letter to NHS Improvement and (b) NHS Improvement's letter to NHS trusts of 24 June 2017 on the need for fire safety tests on NHS buildings.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","2019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746927","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent it going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T09:50:18.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746927/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746927/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much additional funding will he make available to local authorities and housing groups to resolve fire safety issues discovered following the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746928","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>Yes.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:29:08.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746928/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746928/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to his announcement of tests of fire safety of NHS premises on 24 June 2017, whether he has made arrangements for the Department for Communities and Local Government to conduct tests on all cladding on NHS premises of the kind being carried out on high-rise residential buildings.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","2020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746929","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-07","<p>The UK has made considerable progress so far in extending ultrafast broadband through full fibre and other connectivity technologies. According to thinkbroadband, over 52% of the UK has access to ultrafast speeds of 100 Megabits per second or more.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s aim is to provide ultrafast connectivity to as many businesses and homes as possible. We will achieve this by developing approaches to show how new investment from government and the private sector could transform the UK’s full fibre availability. We have set in train our investment plans for extending full fibre, investing £200m to fund locally-led projects across the UK to leverage local and commercial investment in full fibre, beginning the first wave of projects in 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We are preparing plans to introduce a full fibre connection voucher for companies across the country by 2018. As we announced on the 3<sup>rd</sup> July, the £400 million Digital Infrastructure Investment Fund will unlock over £1 billion for full fibre broadband, and kick-start better broadband connections across the country. Further information can be found here (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/billion-pound-connectivity-boost-to-make-buffering-a-thing-of-the-past" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/billion-pound-connectivity-boost-to-make-buffering-a-thing-of-the-past</a>)</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-07T09:45:59.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746929/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746929/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-29","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent steps she has taken to prepare for the roll-out of ultrafast broadband.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746930","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Department expects clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to assure themselves that they have satisfied their legal duties, including the need to consult local populations. CCGs have a duty to consult on their commissioning plans as set out in Section 14Z13 of the NHS Act 2006. The duty does not set any absolute timeframes.</p><p> </p><p>The Dudley CCG undertook a full public consultation last summer to inform the development of the Multi-speciality Community Provider contract. The consultation exercise reached out to several thousand people (including staff) and received over 600 contributions.</p><p> </p><p>A report was commissioned from ICF Consulting Services on the consultation process and considered by the CCG Board in September 2016. A copy of the report is available on the Dudley CCG’s website.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-04T14:35:51.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746930/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746930/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Health Services: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the timescale for consultation for Dudley's multi-specialty community provider complies with the statutory requirements for public bodies.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","2021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746931","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-05","<p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder. Contracts published prior to 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive</a></p><p> </p><p>Those published after 26 February 2015 can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-05T16:24:34.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746931/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746931/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-29","Galliford Try","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many public contracts have been awarded to Galliford Try in (a) Easington constituency and (b) the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746932","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The commissioner – in this case Dudley Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) – is solely responsible for carrying out the procurement and it will be for the commissioner to determine break points, penalties, compensation and arrangements to ensure continuity of service.</p><p> </p><p>As with all standard National Health Service contracts, we would expect any multi-speciality community provider (MCP) contract to set out the circumstances in which the contract may be terminated by either party and the process following termination. It will be for the CCG to determine where the break points should be, factoring in the potential impacts on value for money. In accordance with the existing terms of the NHS Standard Contract, there will be a 12 month no fault termination clause.</p><p> </p><p>The Dudley MCP contract will ensure that in the event of a provider not meeting their obligations, and where there is a need for an early termination, the provider will be required to pay the commissioners any additional costs and expenses incurred as a result of the termination. This will include those incurred in recommissioning the services covered by the contract from an alternative provider for the rest of the term of the contract as well as ensuring service continuity.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","2023 ; 2024","2017-07-04T14:41:22.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746932/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746932/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Health Services: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what provisions have been made to ensure continuity of services in the event of a failure of Dudley's multi-specialty community provider.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","2022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746933","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>Under the reinvigorated Right to Buy we are firmly committed to making sure that for every additional home sold an additional one will be provided. There is a rolling 3 year deadline for local authorities to deliver additional affordable homes through new build or acquisition under the reinvigorated Right to Buy, and so far they have delivered within sales profile. By April 2014 after the first 2 years of the policy there had been 10,933 additional sales and by April 2017 there had been 12,472 starts and acquisitions.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-06T15:10:51.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746933/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746933/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he  will make it his policy to replace all homes sold under right to buy on at least a one-for-one basis.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746934","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Libraries Taskforce’s strategy document, Libraries Deliver: Ambition for Public Libraries in England 2016 to 2021, sets out a bold and dynamic vision of how library services in England can help transform lives, communities and society as a whole. This includes more people, including children, benefitting from the range of services provided by libraries. Examples of initiatives to encourage increased access by children to libraries include a voluntary scheme introduced by Hampshire County Council that provides parents with the opportunity to sign up their new born babies to their library at the time of registering their birth. The Summer Reading Challenge which promotes reading for children at their local library has resulted in many thousands of children aged 4 – 11 joining a library.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-07-17T15:14:25.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746934/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746934/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-29","Public Libraries: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she plans to bring forward a strategy to ensure that all children have access to local library services.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746935","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) has significantly increased the funding invested in cyber security for Defence over the last five years. In the 2015-2020 spending review period, MOD's total commitment to cyber security programmes and capabilities is approximately £2.5 billion.</p><p>The MOD does not tackle the technical issues of cyber security in isolation: our approach to cyber security spans technical, organisational, procedural, policy and physical measures. As investment is integrated across all of these areas, and across different teams within MOD, it is not possible to give a figure purely for UK cyber security. However, I can provide examples of the investments the MOD has been making in cyber over the last five years.</p><p>In July 2013, we announced that the MOD had allocated £70 million from the Defence budget for improving cyber security capabilities over four years.</p><p>In July 2014, the Prime Minister announced a package of investment in equipment for our Armed Forces, which included £75 million over four years specifically for cyber defence.</p><p>In 2015, the National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review made clear that cyber security remains a national priority and made clear Defence's roles in cyberspace. £1.9 billion was pledged to deliver the National Cyber Security Strategy (NCSS) over the Spending Review period (2015-2020).</p><p>In 2016, over £40 million was allocated for the Cyber Security Operations Centre. This is a dedicated facility staffed by experts that utilises state-of-the-art defensive cyber capabilities to protect the MOD's cyberspace from malicious actors. A further £265 million is being invested in a pioneering approach to root out cyber vulnerabilities within our military platforms and wider cyber dependent systems.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-05T15:54:27.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746935/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746935/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-29","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much funding his Department has allocated to UK cyber security in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746936","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>I have every sympathy for the victims of terrorist violence, for which there could be no possible justification.<strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>My officials have been working closely with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) in relation to the Government’s response to the Northern Ireland Affairs Committee’s report on support for UK victims of IRA attacks that used Gaddafi-supplied semtex and weapons, published on 2 May 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government intends to submit its response to the report after the summer recess. My officials will continue to engage closely with the FCO on this issue.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-07-06T14:21:47.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746936/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746936/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-06-29","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions he has had with the Foreign Secretary on obtaining compensation from Libya for the UK victims of Gaddafi-sponsored IRA terrorism; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746938","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-07","<p>Highways England is awaiting validated accident data for 2016, and will review the position in light of this information.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-07T09:40:06.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746938/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746938/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-29","A19: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 26 June 2017 to Question 336 on A19: accidents, if he will commission a report into the causes of injuries and fatalities at accident blackspots on the A19.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746939","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>Under the Representation of the People Act 1983 local authorities who are responsible for designating polling places, within which polling stations are located must seek to ensure that so far as is reasonable and practicable every polling place for which it is responsible is accessible to electors who are disabled.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government has established the accessibility to elections working group, including MENCAP and RNIB, and is determined to ensure that all polling stations are as accessible as possible in order to ensure people with disabilities can participate fully in our democracy.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-07T12:33:31.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746939/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746939/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-29","Polling Stations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will introduce legislation to require all polling stations to be accessible to people with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746940","Department of Health","false","2017-07-07","<p>The Government remains committed to reforming nursing, midwifery and allied health pre-registration education and increasing the number of places available for students for students so that two in three nursing applicants are no longer turned down for a place; at the same time ensuring these students have more cash available to them while they study.</p><p> </p><p>Universities and Colleges Admissions Service data show that up to March 2017 there had been around two nurse applicants per available training place. Health Education England is confident that the National Health Service will have the required number of students it needs starting courses this year and will continue to work with the education sector to deliver these reforms successfully for the longer term.</p><p> </p><p>It should also be noted that students will continue to apply for courses up to September and through clearing.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-07T09:55:29.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746940/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746940/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make representations to the Department for Health to reintroduce NHS bursaries to reduce the need for overseas recruitment.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746941","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety submitted its final report in April 2017. I had intended to publish the report then, but the announcement of the General Election prevented me from doing so.</p><p> </p><p>Following the Grenfell Tower fire tragedy, I asked the Working Group to urgently review their findings and their report has been published today.</p><p> </p><p>I have also asked the Working Group to look at further potential areas of product safety and recalls where action might be required, in light of the tragic events at Grenfell Tower.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T15:14:17.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746941/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746941/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-29","Product Recalls and Safety Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety will publish its report.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746942","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database has not identified any items of correspondence received from Health Education England about the effect of the removal of National Health Service bursaries on staff recruitment.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has regular meetings on workforce policy (including nurse supply) that Health Education England attend.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-06T14:11:26.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746942/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746942/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations has he received from Health Education England on the effect of the removal of NHS bursaries on staff recruitment.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746943","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>Information on family settlement visas is published quarterly in the Immigration Statistics which are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/list-of-tables#visas</a>.</p><p> </p><p>A temporary hold on decision-making in respect of some settlement visa applications was introduced on 22 February 2017 so that the implications of the Supreme Court judgment handed down that day in MM (Lebanon) &amp; Others could be considered. The temporary hold will be lifted once the judgment’s findings have been addressed.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-10T10:17:02.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746943/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746943/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Visas: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for settlement visas have been (a) rejected, (b) processed and (c) paused since 22 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","2082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746944","Department for Education","false","2017-07-24","<p>I am sorry, but the Department does not hold information about correspondence sent by Parliamentary Private Secretaries, and the information about Ministers’ correspondence is not available other than at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-24T14:57:19.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746944/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746944/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-29","Department for Education: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department spent on correspondence that was sent by (a) Ministers and (b) Parliamentary Private Secretaries in each financial year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","2084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746945","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>On 5 September 2017, we published consolidated advice for building owners following large-scale testing which can be viewed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing</a></p><p>The results include a category for public buildings, which includes hospitals and schools. This shows that there were 16 buildings in England with Aluminium Composite Material (ACM), all of which have cladding systems which the Expert Panel advise are unlikely to meet current Building Regulations guidance and therefore present fire hazards on buildings over 18 metres. All government departments have been assessing their estate for high-rise buildings with ACM cladding.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T15:07:53.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746945/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746945/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746945/answer/previousversion/1903","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-29","Public Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2017 to Question 588, what (a) number and (b) proportion of public sector buildings where people are (i) required and (ii) not required to sleep overnight have had their cladding tested; and when he expects all such buildings in each group to have been tested.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","2088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746946","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-06","<p>A key part of the industrial strategy is to drive growth across the whole country. To do this, the Department is committed to working with local partners. This is why we have provided £380 million growth deal funding for the North East Local Enterprise Partnership. We continue to work with that partnership to support their growth plans for the private and public sectors across the North East, including Easington.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-06T14:36:19.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746946/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746946/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-29","Business and Public Sector: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will bring forward proposals to encourage public sector bodies and private companies to relocate to Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746947","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The consultation closed on 17 April, and the responses to this are currently being considered.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-04T14:28:51.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746947/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746947/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department will issue a formal response to the consultation on Special Category Mechanism and Financial and Other Support in England, published on 6 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","2089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746948","Home Office","false","2017-07-04","<p>Greater Manchester Police has indicated that they will be making a Special Grant claim in relation to the additional policing costs incurred as a result of the terrorist attack at Manchester Arena. Once this has been received, Ministers will consider it carefully and respond as soon as practicable.</p><p>We know that the recent horrific attacks have put pressure on the police across the country. We are already working closely with policing, to help manage the cost of the immediate response.</p><p>We also have a constructive dialogue with policing to ensure that the right powers, capabilities and resources are in place.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-04T11:08:50.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746948/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746948/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Criminal Investigation: Manchester Arena","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what additional financial support her Department is providing to Greater Manchester Police to meet the costs resulting from the investigation into the terrorist attack at Manchester Arena on 22 May 2017.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746949","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>I recognise the efforts Whirlpool has made to rectify the safety issue which affected certain models of tumble dryers; with over 1.5 million appliances modified or replaced.</p><p> </p><p>However, I remain concerned that there are many unregistered appliances in use across the UK and my officials remain in close contact Whirlpool and Peterborough City Council Trading Standards to ensure the company contacts those consumers with an affected machine who have not yet signed up for a repair or replacement.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T15:14:24.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746949/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746949/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-29","Tumble Dryers: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with Whirlpool on the safety of tumble dryers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746950","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-06","<p>The government introduced the National Living Wage in April 2016, which benefitted around 1.7 million low paid workers and delivered the fastest wage growth for the lowest paid in 20 years. Furthermore, the government has boosted take home pay with increases to personal allowance, where 1.3 million individuals will be taken out of income tax this year.</p><p> </p><p>The government is also investing in young people, through expanding the apprenticeship programme in England increasing spending on apprenticeships to £2.5bn in 2019-20. Budget 2017 also announced an additional £500m to be invested each year in England’s technical education system. This will help give young people the skills they need to succeed in the world of work.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-06T13:34:24.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746950/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746950/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-29","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to tackle wage stagnation among young people and low wage earners.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746951","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>The number of accidental primary fires in England where the fire and rescue service recorded the ignition power source for the fire as electric decreased from 34,431 in 2010/11 to 30,136 in 2015/16. There are no plans to commission research on this topic.</p><p>The number of accidental dwelling fires where the ignition power source was ‘electric’ decreased from 19,603 in 2010/11 to 18,288 in 2014/15. The Home Department has not estimated the costs of these fires.</p><p>See fire statistics table FIRE0605. (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#cause-of-fire" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#cause-of-fire</a>)</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2124","2017-08-04T12:56:48.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746951/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746951/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Domestic Appliances: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will commission research into the reasons for the growth in the number of electrical fires.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746952","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>The UK has one of the highest sets of product safety requirements in the EU which requires goods to meet strict safety rules before they are put into use.</p><p> </p><p>The Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety submitted its final report in April 2017. I had intended to publish the report then, but the announcement of the General Election prevented me from doing so.</p><p> </p><p>Following the Grenfell Tower fire tragedy, I asked the Working Group to urgently review their findings and their report has been published today.</p><p> </p><p>I have also asked the Working Group to look at further potential areas of product safety and recalls where action might be required, in light of the tragic events at Grenfell Tower.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T15:14:40.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746952/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746952/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-29","High Rise Flats: Domestic Appliances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on the provision of safety tests for white goods which are located in tower blocks.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746953","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>The UK system of product safety requires white goods to meet strict safety requirements before they are put into use. Where faults occur, Trading Standards have powers to order recalls or other corrective actions.</p><p> </p><p>Consumers can check for the latest information on recalls on the GOV.UK website searching for ‘product recall campaign’.</p><p> </p><p>The Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety submitted its final report in April 2017. I had intended to publish the report then, but the announcement of the General Election prevented me from doing so.</p><p> </p><p>Following the Grenfell Tower fire tragedy, I asked the Working Group to urgently review their findings and their report has been published today.</p><p> </p><p>I have also asked the Working Group to look at further potential areas of product safety and recalls where action might be required, in light of the tragic events at Grenfell Tower.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T15:14:48.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746953/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746953/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-29","Domestic Appliances: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make a statement on how best to ensure that fridge freezers and other white goods are safe for use.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746954","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-06","<p>The European Recycling Platform is an independent company that provides regulatory compliance services to businesses across a number of countries including UK. The Government does not manage this company.</p><p> </p><p>The Repeal Bill will ensure the whole body of existing EU environmental law (including the Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Regulations 2013) continues to have effect in UK law, providing businesses and stakeholders with maximum certainty as we leave the EU.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-07-06T14:43:46.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746954/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746954/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-29","Waste Management: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what his policy is on retaining the European Recycling Platform scheme and the Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment regulations after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746955","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-04","<p>Allegations of chemical weapons use in Syria have continued, mostly alleging use of chlorine by the regime. The Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons' (OPCW) Fact Finding Mission looks at such allegations to determine whether there is sufficient evidence to investigate, and if so to determine whether chemical weapons were used. We condemn all use of chemical weapons and continue to work with partners to ensure credible allegations are investigated. We welcome the latest report of the OPCW Fact-Finding Mission of 29 June, confirming the use of sarin at Khan Sheikhoun on 4 April, as an important step in holding to account those responsible.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-07-04T15:47:18.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746955/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746955/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-29","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received of attacks involving the use of chemical weapons, including chlorine gas, by any party to the conflict in Syria since 4 April 2017; and what assessment he has made of any such reports.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","2114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746956","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-05","<p>The Government has no plans for a new Parliamentary vote on military action to prevent the use of chemical weapons in Syria. We continue to support appropriate actions with our US allies to prevent their use.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-07-05T15:56:13.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746956/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746956/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-29","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether any use of military force against the Syrian Government would require a vote in the House before military action took place; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","2115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-04","<p>We share the strong international concern about chemical weapons use in Syria and regularly discuss the international response at the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) and the UN, as well as bilaterally, with key partners including the US. We fully supported the US action on 7 April as an appropriate response to the use of sarin nerve gas by the Asad regime against Khan Sheikhoun. As the Secretary of State for Defence said on 27 June, the Government would support similar US action in the future. It is important that the international community does all it can to deter further chemical weapons attacks. As I said in my statement on 30 June following the OPCW's confirmation that sarin was used in the Khan Sheikhoun attack, I urge our partners to unite behind the need to hold those responsible for this atrocity to account.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-07-04T15:58:05.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746957/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-29","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the US on a potential military response to another attack by Syrian Government forces in which chemical weapons are used; what plans the Government has to participate in any potential military actions carried out by the US against the Syrian Government in response to such an attack; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","2116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746958","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Prime Minister has tasked the Chairman of the Joint Intelligence Committee to provide the National Security Council with frequently updated assessments of the information held by the government and our allies on matters of this nature. It would not be appropriate, for reasons of national security, to make these assessments public.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:16:44.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746958/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746958/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-29","Chemical Weapons: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment the Joint Intelligence Committee has made of the claim by the US Administration that preparations for an imminent attack using chemical weapons are being made by the Syrian Government.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","2118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746959","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>My department has regular discussions with the National Fire Chiefs Council and individual fire and rescue services on their preventative work.</p><p>We have invested in the Fire Kills campaign and Electrical Safety Week, run in close partnership with fire and rescue authorities in England, which promotes a range of domestic safety messages including on electrical fire safety, to ensure householders take appropriate action to prevent accidental fires and understand how best they can protect themselves and their families.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-07T15:30:26.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746959/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746959/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Domestic Appliances: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with fire and rescue services on preventing and reducing the number of electrical fires in domestic dwellings.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746960","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>I refer the honourable member to the statement by the Foreign Secretary on 18 April 2017 which provides the government's assessment of the attack in Khan Sheikhoun, Syria on 4 April.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:18:33.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746960/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746960/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-29","Chemical Weapons: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the Joint Intelligence Committee's findings on the chemical weapons attack on 4 April 2017 in Khan Sheikhoun.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","2119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746961","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>The number of accidental primary fires in England where the fire and rescue service recorded the ignition power source for the fire as electric decreased from 34,431 in 2010/11 to 30,136 in 2015/16. There are no plans to commission research on this topic.</p><p>The number of accidental dwelling fires where the ignition power source was ‘electric’ decreased from 19,603 in 2010/11 to 18,288 in 2014/15. The Home Department has not estimated the costs of these fires.</p><p>See fire statistics table FIRE0605. (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#cause-of-fire" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#cause-of-fire</a>)</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2098","2017-08-04T12:56:48.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746961/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746961/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Domestic Appliances: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the cost to the public purse of electrical fires in the home.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746962","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>We are currently undertaking a review of the Fire Kills campaign and the impact of recent events will be considered within the review.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-07T15:45:11.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746962/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746962/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to expand the Fire Kills campaign.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746963","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Government is considering what further support it can provide to tackle alcohol harms, focusing on vulnerable groups including families and children.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-04T10:59:25.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746963/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746963/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Alcoholism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will bring forward a strategy to support the children of alcoholics.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","2126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746964","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Ellesmere Port and Neston on 27 June 2017 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=852" target="_blank">852</a>.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:45:29.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746964/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746964/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much he expects to be saved through 2017's NHS capped expenditure process.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","2127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746965","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Prime Minister has tasked the Chairman of the Joint Intelligence Committee to provide the National Security Council with frequently updated assessments of the information held by the government and our allies on matters of this nature. It would not be appropriate, for reasons of national security, to make these assessments public.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-07-10T14:19:37.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746965/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746965/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-29","Chemical Weapons: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will request an independent assessment by the Joint Intelligence Committee of the (a) total size of the Syrian Government's stockpile of chemical weapons, (b) number and location of facilities at which chemical weapons are stored by the Syrian Government, (c) number and location of facilities involved in the production of chemical weapons on behalf of the Syrian Government and (d) likelihood of another attack by Syrian Government forces in which chemical weapons are used; and if he will publish a summary of that assessment.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","2120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746966","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>These data are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.ucas.com/corporate/data-and-analysis/ucas-undergraduate-releases/2017-cycle-applicant-figures-%E2%80%93-march-deadline" target="_blank">www.ucas.com/corporate/data-and-analysis/ucas-undergraduate-releases/2017-cycle-applicant-figures-%E2%80%93-march-deadline</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:44:30.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746966/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746966/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many students applied for (a) nursing and (b) midwifery degrees in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","2128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746967","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-04","<p>On 23 June the UN Human Rights Council agreed by consensus to establish an international investigation into the violence and human rights violations and abuses and violations of international humanitarian law in the Kasai regions of the Democratic Republic of the Congo. The text of the resolution establishing the investigation states that it should be carried out “in accordance with international standards and practice”, which will ensure that the investigation is impartial and independent. During the negotiations the UK worked closely with other members of the Human Rights Council to ensure that a consensus could be found that both ensured the independence of the investigation and recognised the importance of national investigations into the violence.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-04T13:59:39.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746967/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746967/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-29","Democratic Republic of Congo: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to support the UN Human Rights Council Resolution to establish an international investigation into violence and human rights violations in the Kasai region of the Democratic Republic of Congo.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746968","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>The application cycle for student nurse intake in autumn 2017 is ongoing. Applicants can continue to apply until the end of June or can enter clearing following A Level results in August. The last publication from the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) in March 2017 showed that there were 40,560 applicants for the 23,237 commissioned nursing and midwifery courses in England. UCAS will continue to release updated information about the number of offers made by universities and acceptances from candidates with the next update covering applications to the end of June.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:42:25.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746968/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746968/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many students he expects to begin (a) nursing and (b) midwifery degrees in each English university in (i) September 2017 and (ii) later entry periods for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","2129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746969","Department of Health","false","2017-07-04","<p>All patients deserve to be treated with dignity and respect. The Government has made it clear that providers of National Health Service-funded care are expected to eliminate mixed-sex accommodation, except where this is in the overall best interest of the patient, or reflects their personal choice.</p><p>Any hospital that places patients in mixed-sex accommodation can face fines of £250 per patient, per day.</p><p>The NHS Constitution (first published in March 2012) introduced a pledge under “Respect, consent and confidentiality”:</p><p> </p><p>- “that if you are admitted to hospital, you will not have to share sleeping accommodation with patients of the opposite sex, except where appropriate, in line with the details set out in the handbook to the NHS Constitution”</p><p> </p><p>In December 2010, the national reporting of breaches in relation to sleeping accommodation commenced and is collected monthly from all NHS providers and organisations that provide NHS-funded care (including Independent and Voluntary Sector organisations). From April 2011 the collection became mandatory.</p><p>Delivering zero breaches for every trust, every month, is unlikely. This is because it is occasionally right to mix patients (e.g. if a patient is admitted in the middle of the night and the only way to release an appropriate bed would be to awaken and move other patients). In such cases, the breach should be rectified as soon as possible.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-04T16:43:11.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746969/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746969/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-29","Hospital Wards: Gender","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his policy is on the use of mixed-sex wards in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","2130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746970","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-04","<p>SDG4 represents an ambitious expansion of the education agenda from a focus on access to basic education to a focus on learning for all children.</p><p>Despite significant progress on access over the last 15 years, the challenge of implementing the SDG is significant. Over a quarter of a billion children remain out of school, particularly those in crises, and amongst socially excluded groups (including girls, refugees and children with disability). Furthermore the quality of education is a major concern.</p><p>As one of the largest bilateral donors to basic education the UK will continue to prioritise improvements to the quality and effectiveness of education. We will also work with the international community to ensure all boys and girls - especially those who are marginalised, displaced or in fragile states – have access to a decent education and are learning.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-04T14:20:21.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746970/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746970/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-06-29","Sustainable Development: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make a statement on the achievability of Sustainable Development Goal number four on inclusive and equitable quality education and lifelong learning opportunities for all.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746971","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-04","<p>Details of the costs associated with the Article 50 case will be published in due course.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-04T16:09:15.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746971/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746971/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-06-29","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the total cost to the public purse was of the (a) High Court case and (b) Supreme Court appeal on Article 50.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","2135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746972","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>In October 2016 Ministers set up a new Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety to look at options to further improve the safety of white goods and the recall system.</p><p> </p><p>The Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety submitted its final report in April 2017. I had intended to publish the report then, but the announcement of the General Election prevented me from doing so.</p><p> </p><p>Following the Grenfell Tower fire tragedy, I asked the Working Group to urgently review their findings and their report has been published today.</p><p> </p><p>I have also asked the Working Group to look at further potential areas of product safety and recalls where action might be required, in light of the tragic events at Grenfell Tower.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T15:14:33.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746972/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746972/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-29","Consumers: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to improve and strengthen the UK product recall system to ensure it is focused on public safety.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746973","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>Mobile phone chargers are currently captured under the category ‘battery charger’ in the Incident Recording System, tablets under the ‘pc’ category and e-cigarettes can be recorded in an ‘other’ category.</p><p>Home Office officials have regular discussions with fire and rescue services and other users of fire statistics, including the Fire and Rescue Statistics User Group. Feedback from these groups, including how to best capture new technology, will be used to inform an update of the categories in the Incident Recording System at the next opportunity. Any additions to fire data collections are governed by the Single Data List process to ensure that the burden of any new data collection is considered.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2145 ; 2146","2017-08-04T14:44:21.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746973/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746973/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-29","Electronic Equipment: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her policy is on the inclusion of (a) mobile phone chargers and (b) e-cigarettes in fire statistics released by her Department.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","2144"
