"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746370","Department of Health","false","2017-07-03","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-03T15:45:34.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746370/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746370/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-28","Mental Health Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the NHS has paid private healthcare companies for the provision of (a) eating disorder and (b) mental health services in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","1736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746371","Department of Health","false","2017-07-03","<p>Public Health England regularly engages with the charities and third sector bodies that make up the Mental Health Policy Group, plus others in the national mental health sector, all of whom are independent from government.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-03T13:37:58.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746371/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746371/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-28","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many times (a) a representative from Public Health England and (b) the Chief Executive of Public Health England has attended meetings of the Mental Health Policy Group since 1 February 2016; and on which date each such meeting was held.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","1737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746372","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-03","<p>The Department publishes a range of Official Statistics on PIP here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>These include data tables showing a breakdown of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claims in payment by their main disabling condition.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-03T09:32:59.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746372/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746372/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-06-28","Personal Independence Payment: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of people in receipt of personal independence payments have a mental illness.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","1738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746373","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-03","<p>​The two mile runway at Wideawake Airfield requires a full-depth resurfacing. The runway is owned and operated by the US Air Force under the Bahamas Agreement. Therefore, they are responsible for the design, management and delivery of the resurfacing project. The design phase is already underway but Ascension's isolated location and the complexity of these repairs mean works are not expected to be completed until 2020.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-07-03T16:43:15.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746373/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746373/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-28","Ascension Island: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the timetable is for the commencement and conclusion of maintenance to the Wideawake Airfield on Ascension Island; and what the reasons are for that repair not having begun.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","1739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746374","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>The Department has discussed the viability of The Kingsway Academy with the Local Authority (LA) and the Northern Schools Trust (NST) on several occasions since October 2016. The Secretary of State has agreed the school should close by the end of 2017/18 and the Department is working closely with the LA and NST to plan the transition for pupils. The school site will remain in LA ownership and the Department will work with the LA on options for its future use.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","1752 ; 1892 ; 1893","2017-07-03T16:32:52.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746374/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746374/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-28","Kingsway Academy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the Government first became aware of Northern Schools Trust's intention to close Kingsway Academy; and what steps her Department is taking to provide new school places for that Academy's pupils in the event of closure.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","1751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746375","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>There was no education bill in Her Majesty's Most Gracious Speech, and therefore the ban on opening new grammar schools will remain in place. I will confirm spending plans within the education budget in due course.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2017-07-03T14:15:34.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746375/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746375/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-28","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how the funding will be allocated that was pledged to new grammar schools in the 2015-2017 Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","1774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746376","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>The Department has discussed the viability of The Kingsway Academy with the Local Authority (LA) and the Northern Schools Trust (NST) on several occasions since October 2016. The Secretary of State has agreed the school should close by the end of 2017/18 and the Department is working closely with the LA and NST to plan the transition for pupils. The school site will remain in LA ownership and the Department will work with the LA on options for its future use.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","1751 ; 1892 ; 1893","2017-07-03T16:32:52.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746376/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746376/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746376/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-28","Kingsway Academy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with Northern Schools Trust on the potential closure of Kingsway Academy in Wallasey; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","1752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746377","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-03","<p>Legal fees of defending the case in the High Court are £67,690. This figure includes VAT where payable (for example on Counsel’s fees) and disbursements but does not include costs attributable to time spent by Government advisory lawyers, as time spent by such advisory lawyers is not recorded in a manner that allows it to be attributable to individual court cases.</p><p> </p><p>DWP has also paid £125,000 (plus VAT) towards the Claimants’ costs.</p><p> </p><p>DWP’s legal costs for appealing the case in the Court of Appeal are estimated to be between £25,000 and £40,000 (this includes our best estimate of external Counsel fees).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-03T14:09:52.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746377/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746377/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746377/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-06-28","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost was to the public purse of legal fees in relation to defending the benefit cap in the High Court; and how much his Department estimates the cost of appealing the High Court's decision on that case will be.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","1771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746378","Department for Education","false","2017-07-11","<p>We recently consulted on a national funding formula for schools. We believe that the current funding arrangements are unfair and we remain committed to changing them.</p><p> </p><p>We received over 25,000 responses to the consultation, which we are analysing in detail. We are grateful to all those who expressed their views on school funding and the proposed formula as part of this process. We will publish the response to the consultation in due course. Until then, we are unable to confirm the funding each school will receive in future years.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-11T16:56:41.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746378/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746378/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746378/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-28","Pupils: Tatton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the projected (a) cash and (b) per pupil funding will be for schools in Tatton constituency in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Esther McVey","Tatton","Esther McVey","1714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746379","Department of Health","false","2017-07-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Ellesmere Port and Neston on 27 June 2017 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=852" target="_blank">852</a>.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-07-06T14:04:45.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746379/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746379/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746379/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-28","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much the capped expenditure process in the NHS is estimated to save in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Ms Marie Rimmer","1716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746380","Home Office","false","2017-07-05","<p>Intelligence exchange between UK law enforcement and Europol is well-established and routine, including on organised immigration crime. The National Crime Agency and Immigration Enforcement also support Europol with seconded staff, including within the European Migrant Smuggling Centre (EMSC), which incorporates JOT Mare. This cooperation has and continues to assist UK efforts to tackle organised immigration crime impacting on the UK.</p><p>However, the data requested is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1711 ; 1713 ; 1719","2017-07-05T15:13:23.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746380/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746380/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-28","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases have been shared through Europol's Joint Operational Team Mare programme by (a) the UK, (b) other EU member states, (c) states with operational agreements with Europol and (d) states with strategic agreements with Europol in each year since that programme's creation in March 2015.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","1724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746381","Department for Education","false","2017-07-27","<p>The Department primarily allocates revenue funding for schools at local authority level, and does not identify funding for primary and secondary schools separately. The table in the attachment shows per pupil revenue funding figures from 2012-13 to 2017-18 for each local authority.</p><p>Figures are not directly comparable from year to year: in 2012-13 local authorities were allocated a General Unit of Funding (GUF), which covered schools, high needs and early years funding. From 2013-14, this was split into separate schools, high needs and early years blocks. Schools block allocations for 2017-18 reflect the most recent spending decisions by individual local authorities, including transfers between the schools and high needs block.</p><p> </p><p>The schools block allocation for all individual schools for 2016-17 are published at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2016-to-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","1613","2017-07-27T17:49:46.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746381/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746381/answer","1613, 1718 attachment.xlsx","1613_1718_attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746381/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-28","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average (a) cash and (b) per pupil funding is for (i) primary and (ii) secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Esther McVey","Tatton","Esther McVey","1718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746382","Home Office","false","2017-07-05","<p>Intelligence exchange between UK law enforcement and Europol is well-established and routine, including on organised immigration crime. The National Crime Agency and Immigration Enforcement also support Europol with seconded staff, including within the European Migrant Smuggling Centre (EMSC), which incorporates JOT Mare. This cooperation has and continues to assist UK efforts to tackle organised immigration crime impacting on the UK.</p><p>However, the data requested is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1711 ; 1713 ; 1724","2017-07-05T15:13:23.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746382/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746382/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-28","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what contributions Europol's Joint Operational Team Mare has made to UK border control operations at (a) Calais and (b) other locations in each year since March 2015.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","1719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746383","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>In a modern, interconnected world, crime is increasingly international and does not respect borders. The Government is clear that effective cooperation with EU Member States on security, justice and policing in order to tackle serious organised crime will continue to be a top UK priority.</p><p> </p><p>The 2015 National Security Strategy (NSS) confirmed that cybercrime is a top threat to the UK’s economic and national security. The UK’s future security and prosperity depends on our ability to safeguard the digital information, data and networks at home and abroad. The cyber threats we face continue to grow in scale and sophistication. The Government will continue to invest in law enforcement capabilities to ensure delivery agencies have the capacity to deal with the increasing volume and sophistication of cyber crime.</p><p> </p><p>The Government values the role of Europol and that is why the UK opted-in to the new Europol Regulation, which came into force on 1 May 2017, enabling us to maintain our current access to the agency and benefit from its cooperation and operational advantages until we leave the EU.</p><p>The Prime Minister has made clear that one of the twelve objectives for the negotiations ahead will be to establish a new relationship with the European Union that includes practical arrangements on matters of law enforcement cooperation to tackle cross-border crime and to keep our people safe.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with EU partners and we are examining the options for future cooperation once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1712 ; 1722 ; 1723","2017-07-07T08:51:23.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746383/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746383/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-28","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect on the UK's ability to fight cybercrime of the UK's potential loss of access to Europol's Joint Cybercrime action taskforce after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","1720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746384","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>In a modern, interconnected world, crime is increasingly international and does not respect borders. The Government is clear that effective cooperation with EU Member States on security, justice and policing in order to tackle serious organised crime will continue to be a top UK priority.</p><p> </p><p>The 2015 National Security Strategy (NSS) confirmed that cybercrime is a top threat to the UK’s economic and national security. The UK’s future security and prosperity depends on our ability to safeguard the digital information, data and networks at home and abroad. The cyber threats we face continue to grow in scale and sophistication. The Government will continue to invest in law enforcement capabilities to ensure delivery agencies have the capacity to deal with the increasing volume and sophistication of cyber crime.</p><p> </p><p>The Government values the role of Europol and that is why the UK opted-in to the new Europol Regulation, which came into force on 1 May 2017, enabling us to maintain our current access to the agency and benefit from its cooperation and operational advantages until we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Intelligence exchange between UK law enforcement and Europol is well-established and takes place on a daily and routine basis on a wide range of criminal activity, including cybercrime. The National Crime Agency (NCA) also support Europol with seconded staff, including within the European Cybercrime Centre (EC3). This cooperation continues to assist UK efforts to tackle cybercrime impacting on the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Since its launch, the UK has submitted 414,776 malware files to the Europol Malware Analysis Solution.</p><p> </p><p>The data requested on how many occasions the UK has received support from the European Cybercrime Centre is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","1562","2017-08-04T12:49:40.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746384/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746384/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-28","Europol","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many files the UK has sent to the Europol Malware Analysis Solution in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","1721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746385","Home Office","false","2017-07-07","<p>In a modern, interconnected world, crime is increasingly international and does not respect borders. The Government is clear that effective cooperation with EU Member States on security, justice and policing in order to tackle serious organised crime will continue to be a top UK priority.</p><p> </p><p>The 2015 National Security Strategy (NSS) confirmed that cybercrime is a top threat to the UK’s economic and national security. The UK’s future security and prosperity depends on our ability to safeguard the digital information, data and networks at home and abroad. The cyber threats we face continue to grow in scale and sophistication. The Government will continue to invest in law enforcement capabilities to ensure delivery agencies have the capacity to deal with the increasing volume and sophistication of cyber crime.</p><p> </p><p>The Government values the role of Europol and that is why the UK opted-in to the new Europol Regulation, which came into force on 1 May 2017, enabling us to maintain our current access to the agency and benefit from its cooperation and operational advantages until we leave the EU.</p><p>The Prime Minister has made clear that one of the twelve objectives for the negotiations ahead will be to establish a new relationship with the European Union that includes practical arrangements on matters of law enforcement cooperation to tackle cross-border crime and to keep our people safe.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work closely with EU partners and we are examining the options for future cooperation once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","1712 ; 1720 ; 1723","2017-07-07T08:51:23.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746385/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/746385/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-28","Europol"